<seg id=1> Lien Hoe is expected to redeem its remaining 65% bond before end of this year </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Kuala Lumpur) Lien Hoe is expected to be able to redeem the remainder of its 65% bond, which totaled 53,810,000 Singapore Dollars before the end of this year, by getting loans from banks and floating other loans. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The Lien Hoe Organization holds the Security Bond with 6% annual interest and the total issued value of 85,740,000 Singapore Dollars, which will be due on August 17, 1998. </seg>
<seg id=4> Due to the decline of the real estate market and the retrenching of the tourist industry, The Lien Hoe Organization can only redeem 35% of its bond at the expiration of its term, the remaining 65% will have to be extended with 15% interest until August 17, 2000. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The Security and Stock Exchange Committee approved the Lien Hoe Organization's extending the term of its bond until August 17, 2000, and it thus becomes the first company to obtain an extension on its bond's term in this country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Since the interest has been dropping, the Lien Hoe Organization planned to borrow new loans and buy back the rest of its bond so that it will not have to pay the higher 15% interest to the bondholders. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The director manager of this company, Hualong, Zhen said that, since the current interest rate has been dropping and the new budget avails development in the real estate industry, the Lien Hoe Organization is expected to change its inferior position of the first half year during the second half year, and to have outstanding performance overall. </seg>
</p>
